caption: War Production Board (WPB) poster. Poster distributed by the WPB to war plants. The original is 28 1/2 inches by 40 inches and is printed in yellow, red and gray on white. Copies may be obtained from war production drive headquarters, WPB, Washington, D.C.

"Save Waste Fats" poster distributed by the War Production Board (WPB) to food stores and salvage committees in cities and towns where salvage campaigns are being conducted. The original is 20 inches by 28 1/2 inches and is printed in red, black and gray and white. Copies may be obtained from Central Distribution Section, Office for Emergency Management (OEM), 1509 14th Street, N.W., Washington, D.C.

Tennessee Valley Authority power and conservation. Fort Loudoun Dam construction. One arm of the cofferdam wall at Fort Loudoun Dam, furthest upstream of the TVA's main Tennessee River projects. Scheduled for closure and first storage of water early in 1943, this dam will create a 15,000-acre lake reaching fifty-five miles upstream to the city of Knoxville. The reservoir will have a useful storage capacity of 126,000 acre-feet. Power installation of 64,000 kilowatts is authorized, with a possible ultimate of 96,000 kilowatts

Production. P-51 ("Mustang) fighter planes. An inspector checks over the work done on a P-51 fighter before it moves to the next assembly position at North American's Inglewood, California, plant. This plant produces the battle-tested B-25 ("Billy Mitchell") bomber, used in General Doolittle's raid on Tokyo, and the P-51 fighter plane which was first brought into prominence by the British raid on Dieppe
